Ghar me सब्ज़िया grow karni hai toh LEAFY VEGGIES 🥬 have to be your first pick to try ! They’re easiest to grow in containers, doesn’t take much space and get ready for harvest in just 45-60 days 💪🏻 For Episode 4 of Grow It Yourself, let’s talk Leafy Greens in Container Gardening What all do you need ? 🥗 4 base ingredients for soil mix - Garden Soil (40%), Vermicompost (30%), Cocopeat (20%) and Construction Sand (10%) 🥗(OPTIONAL) Few extra additions soil ko enrich karne ke liye - Neem Khali, Cow Dung Ash, Bonemeal 🥗 Seeds from a local nursery/seed store 🥗 Broad & Shallow pots - 12 inch length * 6 inch depth is standard My recommendation ? 🟢 Currently aap Spinach, Methi, Pak Choi, Dhaniya, Soya ke seeds laga sakte ho ! 🟢 Lettuce, Radish, Carrot, Beets also do well in containers but save them for your second attempt. Few pointers to keep in mind - ➡️ Soil mix ratio is just a reference figure, thoda upar neeche chalega. Buy the ingredients from a local nursery or Amazon ! Lmk if you need links 👍🏻 ➡️ Leafy greens don’t have deeper root system, so shallow pots/grow bags lena aap. You’ll save up space and grow as much possible in your balcony or terrace. ➡️ You can also add Haldi or Cinnamon powder in the soil mix from your kitchen. They have anti fungal properties to protect your plants. ➡️ During sowing the seeds, add only a thin layer of soil on top. DO NOT dab or press at all. Use a sprayer for watering and keep at indirect light spot till germination takes place. ➡️ Once germination is done, aap pots ko direct sunlight me la sakte ho (pref morning sun) and always keep the soil moist, NOT WET ! Your homegrown chemical-free veggies would be ready for harvest in 6-8 weeks, apne hearty meals me add karo and enjoy 🥙 If you learnt something new today, SHARE this video with your friends and family ❣️ And, SAVE it for your reference later 🙌🏻 #growwhatyoueat #homeandgarden #reels #reelsinstagram #leafygreens #urbanfarming #organicliving #homegrownveggies #diyfood #indianhomes #trendingnow #explore

We cried nonstop the whole first week of her diagnosis. It was so hard to watch her have fun, but know that she was battling this evil monster within her blood stream. We would try to keep her entertained all while try to keep ourselves from crying in front of her. Sometimes we’d have to take turns hiding in the restroom to cry so she wouldn’t see us. And even then, she’d sense it and ask us why we were so sad. 😭 I felt like a mad woman crying everywhere! We didn’t want to see anyone or talk to anyone because all we’d be able to do was cry. We could hardly eat and drink anything. After we talked to the oncologist in the hallway, we prayed and lifted Lola up to the Lord in prayer, but it was only through our mouth and not fully with our heart and soul. We still had our own doubts, anger, confusion, and sadness. It wasn’t until we finally found it in our hearts to fully give our baby up to the Lord that we finally found a sense of peace. We still find ourselves crying here and there, especially at night when we are cuddling her to sleep. But the Lord’s peace dwells within our hearts and his joy gets us through the rough days. Thank you to each and every person who reached out to us. We feel overwhelmed by all the love and support. Even though we didn’t get a chance to respond to everyone, just know that we have read and appreciate all your love and support for us and our baby girl. #blolastrong #fightlolafight #lolawillcomehome #childhoodcancer #cancersucks #godisstillgood

*Just a song! Don’t think too deep* ✨🧑‍🍳🤌🏻 ✨ Paneer Tikka Masala Recipe ✨ Ingredients: • Paneer, cut into thick cubes • For marinade: ginger paste, garlic paste, Greek yogurt, olive oil, chili powder, besan (gram flour), lemon juice, salt • Olive oil for cooking • 1 green pepper, 1/2 red pepper, 1/4 onion, cubed • For sauce: oil, 1/4 onion, green chili, 2 big tomatoes, cashews • Ghee and butter • Deggi mirch (red chili powder), coriander powder, kasuri methi (fenugreek leaves) • Heavy cream • Cilantro for garnish • Paratha or naan for serving Steps: 1. Marinate paneer: Mix ginger paste, garlic paste, Greek yogurt, olive oil, chili powder, besan, lemon juice, and salt. Coat paneer cubes with this paste and set aside. 2. Cook marinated paneer in a skillet until charred. 3. Saute cubed green pepper, red pepper, and onion until charred. 4. For the sauce: Sauté quartered onions, green chili, tomatoes, and cashews. Blend into a smooth sauce. 5. In a separate wok, heat ghee and butter. Saute deggi mirch and coriander powder for a few seconds, then add the blended purée. Crush kasuri methi and add to the sauce. 6. Pour in heavy cream, then add the cooked paneer and veggies. 7. Finish with a swirl of cream and garnish with cilantro. 8. Serve with paratha or naan. Enjoy! #paneer #paneertimkamasala #veg #couple #desifood #brown #malabariparatha #couplegoals #explore #indianfood #multiculturalcouple #couplecooking #interracialcouple
